### Create an event to flag (flags need an existing event id)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/events
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "title": "Test Event for Flags",
    "description": "Event used for flag testing",
    "address": "123 Main St",
    "city": "Cluj-Napoca",
    "dateTime": "2026-08-01T18:00:00",
    "maxParticipants": 50,
    "minAge": 18,
    "maxAge": null
}

### Get all flags (should be empty initially)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/admin/flags

### Creates a flag with a free-text reason
POST http://localhost:8080/api/flags?userId=1
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "reason": "I don't like pizza :(",
    "eventId": 2
}

### Creates a second flag on the same event, different user (no unique constraint - should succeed)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/events/1/flags?userId=2
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "reason": "Inappropriate content"
}

### Get all flags (expect 2 results, each with eventId: 1 populated)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/admin/flags

### Delete flag 1
DELETE http://localhost:8080/api/admin/flags/1

### Get all flags (expect only the second flag left)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/admin/flags

### Restart the app between this request and the previous one to confirm
### flags survive a restart (data now lives in Postgres, not memory)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/admin/flags

### Create a flag for an event id that has no row in Postgres yet
### Known gap: EventRepository is still in-memory, so no `event` rows exist in
### the DB. This is expected to fail with a foreign key violation until
### Event itself is converted to a JPA entity/repository.
POST http://localhost:8080/api/events/999/flags?userId=1
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "reason": "Should fail - event 999 has no row in Postgres"
}
